\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s9\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li1563\ri1714\lin1563\rin1714\fi0\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f0\fs21\lang1033\loch\f0\fs21\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs21\lang1033\i0\b0 ... shall be the supreme law of the Republic and any law or act inconsistent with its provisions shall, unless otherwise provided expressly or by necessary implication in this Constitution, be of no force and effect to the extent of the inconsistency.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Section 4(1) of the Constitution. }}}
}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [8] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Chapter Three of the Constitution sets out the fundamental rights to which every person is entitled under the Constitution and also contains provisions dealing with the way in which the Chapter is to be interpreted by the Courts. It does not deal specifica
lly with the death penalty, but in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i section} 11(2), it prohibits "cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment." There is no definition of what is to be regarded as "cruel, inhuman or degrading" and we therefore have to give meaning to these words our
selves.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [9] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 In {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i S v Zuma and Two Others},{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Constitutional Court Case No. CCT/5/94 (5 April 1995).}}}
 this Court dealt with the approach to be adopted in the interpretation of the fundamental rights enshrined in Chapter Three of the Constitution. It gave its approval to an approach which, whilst paying due regard to the languag
e that has been used, is "generous" and "purposive" and gives expression to the underlying values of the Constitution. Kentridge AJ, who delivered the judgment of the Court, referred with approval{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Id. at para. 15. }}}
 to the following passage in the Canadian case of {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i R v Big M
 Drug Mart Ltd}:  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s9\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li1563\ri1714\lin1563\rin1714\fi0\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f0\fs21\lang1033\loch\f0\fs21\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs21\lang1033\i0\b0 The meaning of a right or freedom guaranteed by the Charter was to be ascertained by an analysis of the {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i purpose} of such a guarantee; it was to be understood, in other words, in the light of the interests it was meant to protect.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s9\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li1563\ri1714\lin1563\rin1714\fi0\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f0\fs21\lang1033\loch\f0\fs21\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s9\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li1563\ri1714\lin1563\rin1714\fi0\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f0\fs21\lang1033\loch\f0\fs21\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs21\lang1033\i0\b0 In my view this analysis is to be undertaken, and the purpose of the right or freedom in question is to be sought by reference to the character and larger objects of the Charter itself, to the language chosen to articulate the specific right or freedom, to
 the historical origins of the concept enshrined, and where applicable, to the meaning and purpose of the other specific rights and freedoms with which it is associated within the text of the Charter. The interpretation should be...a generous rather than l
egalistic one, aimed at fulfilling the purpose of a guarantee and securing for individuals the full benefit of the Charter's protection.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 (1985) 13 CRR 64 at 103. As O'Regan J points out in her concurring judgment, there may possibly be instances where the "generous" and "purposive" interpretations do not coincide. That problem does not arise in the present case. }}}
}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [10] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Without seeking in any way to qualify anything that was said in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Zuma}'s case, I need say no more in this judgment than that {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i section} 11(2) of the Constitution must not be construed in isolation, but in its context, which includes the history and background 
to the adoption of the Constitution, other provisions of the Constitution itself and, in particular, the provisions of Chapter Three of which it is part.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Jaga v D\'f6nges, N.O. and Another 1950 (4) SA 653 (A) at 662-663. }}}
 It must also be construed in a way which secures for "individuals the full measure" of its protection
.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Minister of Home Affairs (Bermuda) v Fisher [1980] AC 319 (PC) at 328-329. }}}
 Rights with which {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i section} 11(2) is associated in Chapter Three of the Constitution, and which are of particular importance to a decision on the constitutionality of the death penalty are included in {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i section} 9, "every person shall have the right to life"
, {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i section} 10, "every person shall have the right to respect for and protection of his or her dignity", and {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i section} 8, "every person shall have the right to equality before the law and to equal protection of the law." Punishment must meet the requirements o
f {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i sections} 8, 9 and 10; and this is so, whether these sections are treated as giving meaning to {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Section} 11(2) or as prescribing separate and independent standards with which all punishments must comply.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 In the analysis that follows sections 8, 9 and 10 are treated together as giving meaning to section 11(2), which is the provision of Chapter Three that deals specifically with punishment. }}}
 }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [11] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Mr. Bizos, who represented the South African government at the hearing of this matter, informed us that the government accepts that the death penalty is a cruel, inhuman and degrading punishment and that it should be declared unconstitutional. The Attorney
 General of the Witwatersrand, whose office is independent of the government, took a different view, and contended that the death penalty is a necessary and acceptable form of punishment and that it is not cruel, inhuman or degrading within the meaning of 
{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i section} 11(2). He argued that if the framers of the Constitution had wished to make the death penalty unconstitutional they would have said so, and  that their failure to do so indicated an intention to leave the issue open to be dealt with by Parliament i
n the ordinary way. It was for Parliament, and not the government, to decide whether or not the death penalty should be repealed, and Parliament had not taken such a decision. }
