\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [15] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 As the judgment in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Pepper}'s case shows, a similar relaxation of the exclusionary rule has apparently taken place in Australia and New Zealand.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Id. at 637 F. }}}
 Whether our Courts should follow these examples and extend the scope of what is admissible as background materia
l for the purpose of interpreting statutes does not arise in the present case. We are concerned with the interpretation of the Constitution, and not the interpretation of ordinary legislation. A constitution is no ordinary statute. It is the source of legi
slative and executive authority. It determines how the country is to be governed and how legislation is to be enacted. It defines the powers of the different organs of State, including Parliament, the executive, and the courts as well as the fundamental ri
ghts of every person which must be respected in exercising such powers. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [16] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 In countries in which the constitution is similarly the supreme law, it is not unusual for the courts to have regard to the circumstances existing at the time the constitution was adopted, including the debates and writings which formed part of the process
. The United States Supreme Court pays attention to such matters, and its judgments frequently contain reviews of the legislative history of the provision in question, including references to debates, and statements made, at the time the provision was adop
ted.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 ROTUNDA AND NOWAK, TREATISE ON CONSTITUTIONAL LAW: SUBSTANCE AND PROCEDURE \'a723.6 (2d ed. 1992). }}}
 The German Constitutional Court also has regard to such evidence.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 In the decision on the constitutionality of life imprisonment, [1977] 45 BVerfGE 187, the German Federal Constitutional Court took into account that life imprisonment was seen by the framers of the constitution as the alternative to the death sentence when
 they decided to abolish capital punishment. KOMMERS, THE CONSTITUTIONAL JURISPRUDENCE OF THE FEDERAL REPUBLIC OF GERMANY 315 (1989). }}}
 The Canadian Supreme Court has held such evidence to be admissible, and has referred to the historical background including the pre-confederation debates for the purpose of interpreti
ng provisions of the Canadian Constitution, although it attaches less weight to such information than the United States Supreme Court does.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Reference re s.94(2) of the Motor Vehicle Act (British Columbia) (1986) 18 CRR 30 at 47-50; United States v Cotroni (1990) 42 CRR 101 at 109; Mahe v Alberta (1990) 46 CRR 193 at 214. }}}
 It also has regard to ministerial statements in Parliament in regard to the purpose of particular legislation.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Irwin Toy Ltd. v Quebec (AG) (1989) 39 CRR 193 at 241. }}}
 In 
India, whilst speeches of individual members of Parliament or the Convention are apparently not ordinarily admissible, the reports of drafting committees can, according to Seervai, "be a helpful extrinsic aid to construction."{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 H M SEERVAI, CONSTITUTIONAL LAW OF INDIA, 3rd ed. (1983) Vol. I, para. 2.35 et seq. }}}
}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Seervai cites Kania CJ in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i A. K. Gopalan v The State}{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 (1950) SCR 88 at 111, as cited in Seervai, id., Vol. II, para. 24.7, note 25. }}}
