\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [33] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The death sentence is a form of punishment which has been used throughout history by different societies. It has long been the subject of controversy.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 An account of the history of the death sentence, the growth of the abolitionist movement, and the application of the death sentence by South African courts is given by Prof. B. van Niekerk in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Hanged by the Neck Until You Are Dead}, (1969) 86 SALJ 457; Profe
ssor E. Kahn in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i The Death Penalty in South Africa}, (1970) 33 THRHR 108; and by Professor G. Devenish in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i The historical and jurisprudential evolution and background to the application of the death penalty in South Africa and its relationship with constituti
onal and political reform}, SACJ (1992) 1. For analysis of trends in capital punishment internationally, see AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL, WHEN THE STATE KILLS...THE DEATH PENALTY V. HUMAN RIGHTS (1989). }}}
 As societies became more enlightened, they restricted the offences for which this penalty could be impos
ed.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 See generally, Amnesty International, {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i The Death Penalty: List of Abolitionist and Retentionist Countries} (December 1, 1993), AI Index ACT 50/02/94. }}}
 The movement away from the death penalty gained momentum during the second half of the present century with the growth of the abolitionist movement. In some countries it is now prohibited in all circumstances, in some it is prohibited save in times of
 war, and in most countries that have retained it as a penalty for crime, its use has been restricted to extreme cases. According to Amnesty International, 1,831 executions were carried out throughout the world in 1993 as a result of sentences of death, of
 which 1,419 were in China, which means that only 412 executions were carried out in the rest of the world in that year.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Amnesty International, {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Update to Death Sentences and executions in 1993}, AI Index ACT 51/02/94. }}}
 Today, capital punishment has been abolished as a penalty for murder either specifically or in practice by almost half the countries o
f the world including the democracies of Europe and our neighbouring countries, Namibia, Mozambique and Angola.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Supra note 43. }}}
 In most of those countries where it is retained, as the Amnesty International statistics show, it is seldom used. }
