\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [40] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The earliest litigation on the validity of the death sentence seems to have been pursued in the courts of the United States of America. It has been said there that the "Constitution itself poses the first obstacle to [the] argument that capital punishment 
is per se unconstitutional".{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Furman v. Georgia, {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i supra} note 34, at 418 (Powell, J., joined by Burger, CJ., Blackmun, J. and Rehnquist, J., dissenting). }}}
 From the beginning, the United States Constitution recognised capital punishment as lawful. The Fifth Amendment (adopted in 1791) refers in specific terms to capital punishment and impliedly recognises its validity. The Fourte
enth Amendment (adopted in 1868) obliges the states, not to "deprive any person of life, liberty, or property, without due process of law" and it too impliedly recognises the right of the states to make laws for such purposes.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 See Furman v. Georgia, {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i supra} note 34. }}}
 The argument that capital pu
nishment is unconstitutional was based on the Eighth Amendment, which prohibits cruel and unusual punishment.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Id.}}}
 Although the Eighth Amendment "has not been regarded as a static concept"{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i Gregg v. Georgia}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 , 428 U.S. 153, 173 (1976)(Stewart, Powell and Stevens, JJ.). }}}
 and as drawing its meaning "from the evolving standards of decency tha
t mark the progress of a maturing society",{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Trop v. Dulles, 356 U.S. 86, 101 (1958). }}}
 the fact that the Constitution recognises the lawfulness of capital punishment has proved to be an obstacle in the way of the acceptance of this argument, and this is stressed in some of the judgments of the Uni
ted States Supreme Court.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i See}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0  Furman v. Georgia, {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i supra} note 34, at 380-384, and at 417-420 (Burger, CJ., and Powell, J., respectively, dissenting). {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i See} also, {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i Gregg v. Georgia}, {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i supra} note 60, at 176-180; and Callins v Collins, 114  S.Ct. 1127 (1994)(judgement denying cert.)(Scalia,
 J., concurring). Those who take the contrary view say that these provisions do no more than recognise the existence of the death penalty at the time of the adoption of the Constitution, but do not exempt it from the cruel and unusual punishment clause. Fu
rman v Georgia at 283-284 (Brennan, J., concurring); People v. Anderson, 493 P.2d 880, 886 (Cal. 1972)(Wright, CJ.). }}}
}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [41] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Although challenges under state constitutions to the validity of the death sentence have been successful,{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i See}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0  infra paras. 91-92.}}}
 the federal constitutionality of the death sentence as a legitimate form of punishment for murder was affirmed by the United States Supreme Court in 
{\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Gregg v. Georgia}.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Supra note 60, at 187. }}}
 Both before and after {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i Gregg}'s case, decisions upholding and rejecting challenges to death penalty statutes have divided the Supreme Court, and have led at times to sharply-worded judgments.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i See}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 , e.g., the concurring opinion of Scalia, J., in Callins v. Collins, {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i supra} note 62; the opinions of Rehnquist, J., concurring in part and dissenting in part, in Lockett v. Ohio, {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i supra} note 66, at 628 et seq., and dissenting in Woodson v. North Carolina,
 {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i supra} note 66, at 308 et seq. }}}
 The decisions ultimately turned on the votes o
f those judges who considered the nature of the discretion given to the sentencing authority to be the crucial factor. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [42] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Statutes providing for mandatory death sentences, or too little discretion in sentencing, have been rejected by the Supreme Court because they do not allow for consideration of factors peculiar to the convicted person facing sentence, which may distinguish
