ncing jury or judge of potentially mitigating factors). }}}
 For the same reason, statutes which allow too wide a discretion to judges or juries have also been struck down on the grounds that the exercise of such discretion leads to arbitrary results.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i See}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0  Green v. Georgia 442 U.S. 95 (1979). }}}
 In sum, therefore, if there 
is no discretion, too little discretion, or an unbounded discretion, the provision authorising the death sentence has been struck down as being contrary to the Eighth Amendment; where the discretion has been "suitably directed and limited so as to minimise
 the risk of wholly arbitrary and capricious action",{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i Gregg v. Georgia}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 , {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i supra} note 60, at 189.}}}
 the challenge to the statute has failed.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf0\sl360\slmult1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\aspalpha\li283\ri0\lin283\rin0\fi-283\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f0\fs20\lang1033\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch   }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Id. {\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i See} also, Proffitt v. Florida, 428 U.S. 242 (1976). The nature of the offence for which the sentence is imposed is also relevant. Coker v. Georgia, 433 U.S. 584 (1977). }}}
