\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [250] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 This, in my view, also accords with {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i ubuntu} - and calls for a balancing of the interest of society against those of the individual, for the maintenance of law and order, but not for dehumanising and degrading the individual. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [251] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 We must stand tallest in these troubled times and realise that every accused person who is sent to jail is not beyond being rehabilitated - properly counselled - or, at the very least, beyond losing the will and capacity to do evil. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [252] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 A further aspect which I wish to mention is the question of traditional African jurisprudence, and the degree to which such values have not been researched for the purposes of the determination of the issue of capital punishment. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [253] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Ms Davids, who appeared on behalf of the Black Advocates Forum, in its capacity as {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i amicus curiae}, touched on but did not fully argue this matter. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [254] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 She submitted that we could not determine the question of the constitutionality or otherwise of the death sentence without reference to further evidence which would include the views, aspirations and opinions of the historically disadvantaged and previousl
y oppressed people of South Africa, who also constitute the majority of our society. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [255] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 As I understood her argument, the issue of capital punishment could not be determined in an open and democratic society without the active participation of the black majority. This, in my view, would be tantamount to canvassing public opinion among the bla
ck population for the decisions of our courts. I do not agree with this submission, if it implies that this Court or any other court must function according to public opinion. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [256] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 In order to arrive at an answer as to the constitutionality or otherwise of the death penalty or any enactment, we do not have to canvass the opinions and attitudes of the public. Ours is to interpret the provisions of the Constitution as they stand and if
 any matter is in conflict with the Constitution, we have to strike it down. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [257] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 We, as judges, are oath bound to defend the Constitution. This obligation, in turn, requires that any enactment of Parliament should be judged by standards laid down by the Constitution. The judiciary has the duty of implementing the constitutional safegua
rds that protect individual rights. When the State seeks to take away the individual fundamental right to life, the safeguards of the Constitution should be examined with special diligence. When it appears that an act of Parliament conflicts with the provi
sions of the Constitution, we have no choice but to enforce the paramount commands of the Constitution. We are sworn to do no less. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [258] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 I agree with Ms Davids' submission about the need to bring in the traditional African jurisprudence to these matters, to the extent that such is applicable, and would not confine such research to South Africa only, but to Africa in general. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [259] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 For purposes of the determination of the question of the constitutionality of the death penalty, however, it is, in my view, not necessary or even desirable that public opinion should be sought on the matter in the manner she suggests. }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\f4\f4\sl360\slmult1\qj [260] \tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s7\cf0\sl360\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\aspalpha\li1208\ri0\lin1208\rin0\fi-760\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\fs24\lang1033\loch\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 In my view, the death penalty does not belong to the society envisaged in the Constitution, is clearly in conflict with the Constitution generally and runs counter to the concept of {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i ubuntu}; additionally and just as importantly, it violates the provisions o
f Section 11(2) of the Constitution and, for those reasons, should be declared unconstitutional and of no force and effect. }
